    <node id="The woman, named Jake, values the man's ability to walk again above all else, as she believes it is the key for him to continue being a part of the Space Corps. This is evident through her dedicated efforts in caring for him and helping him recover from his neuro-pistol wound.&#10;&#10;The source of hope for both Jake and the man lies in his past achievement of becoming a Space Corps officer. For Jake, the man's status as an officer represents their shared dream of staying in space and working with rockets, despite his current situation as a fugitive charged with second degree murder and escape. The trite words associated with being a Space Officer—honesty, loyalty, duty—symbolize the values that have allowed humanity to break free from the limitations of Earth and explore the stars.&#10;&#10;For the man, his past achievement serves as both a source of hope and guilt. He reminisces about the Space Corps' principles and the sacrifices made by those in the organization, such as Everson's successful Moon landing after three failures and a hundred men dead. This reminder of what he once stood for fuels his desire to rejoin the Space Corps and continue working with rockets, which is why walking again becomes his primary focus. However, the man also grapples with guilt from his past actions and the constant haunting memory of the person whose face he can't forget.&#10;&#10;In summary, Jake's main concern is helping the man walk again so that they can both continue pursuing their shared dream of working in space. The man finds hope in rejoining the Space Corps and leaving his past failures and guilt behind, allowing him to focus on a future filled with rockets and space exploration." />
