    <node id="The person in the room has been recovering from a neuro-pistol wound, which involved paralysis due to the effects of a substance called mortocain. This is evident from the symptoms they experienced earlier, such as a pricking sensation followed by growing paralysis and swelling of the body, as well as the need for an oxygen mask, electric blankets, and liquid food administered through a tube. The kind figure providing care and assistance is a girl, likely between 25 and 30 years old, who has been taking care of the person for nine days, carrying them when they were shot, and helping them recover by providing massage, possibly administering anti-paralysis injections, and ensuring adequate rest. The person wakes up from a period of lethargy to find themselves in a small room with a cracked, unpainted ceiling and a single round window, with the girl standing next to their bedside, asking them if they are feeling better." />
    <node id="1. The people living on the new base built on an asteroid are a group of renegade spacemen who operate beyond Mars. They consist of about a thousand individuals and have a dozen ships. Half of them are wanted by the Interplanetary Bureau of Investigation, while the others are physical or psycho rejects who cannot return to Earth even if they wanted to.&#10;2. These spacemen cannot return to Earth because they are outlaws or rejects who do not fit in with society on Earth. They have established a base on an asteroid where they can operate freely and make an honest living by transporting cargo and supplies to frontier ports like Hoover City. They are described as misfits and rejectees from the clearing houses on Earth, and they have formed their own community beyond the reach of Earth's laws and society." />
    <node id="Ben Curtis, a misfit spaceman who was charged with second degree murder and escape, managed to escape from Hoover City with the help of his friend Jake (who is also a spaceman) and their network of friends. They likely provided Ben with a hiding place in the city, the use of a small desert-taxi, and a pass to leave the city. This allowed him to avoid detection by the authorities as he made his way to the spaceport.&#10;&#10;Once at the spaceport, Ben found a tramp freighter whose skipper was on his last flight before retirement. The crew's discipline was lax and the investigation of new personnel was even more so, which allowed Ben to successfully stow away on the ship. He had also gotten rid of his uniform and changed his name to avoid detection.&#10;&#10;Ben's resourcefulness and luck played a big role in his journey to Venus. He managed to find a way to escape Earth and make his way to Venus, where he hoped to find a red-bearded giant who was rumored to be the leader of a group of renegade spacemen operating beyond Mars. These spacemen had established a base on an asteroid and were living there as outlaws or rejects who could not return to Earth even if they wanted to. They made an honest living by transporting cargo and supplies to frontier ports like Hoover City." />
    <node id="The person is recovering from a neuro-pistol wound, which involved paralysis due to the effects of a substance called mortocain. They have been in a state of lethargy and have woken up in a small room with an oxygen mask, electric blankets, and are being cared for by a kind girl. The girl has been taking care of them for nine days, carrying them when they were shot, and helping them recover through massage, possibly administering anti-paralysis injections, and ensuring adequate rest. The person is unsure of the time or their location but feels more aware after waking up from their latest period of lethargy." />
    <node id="The &quot;dead man&quot; that Ben is trying to find and escape from is named Cobb, a stout and flabby man of about forty who hated spacemen. Ben is haunted by Cobb's image, which appears as a pop-eyed mask of surprise or a frozen face with gaping mouth and trickling blood. Ben wants to forget a living man like Cobb, but his death has made him an invisible Siamese twin to Ben.&#10;&#10;Ben needs to find the man with the red beard to escape from Cobb because he believes that this giant can help him. The story does not provide explicit details about their connection, but it is possible that the red-bearded man is a powerful figure who can protect Ben from Cobb or help him deal with his past as a junior astrogation officer and his current status as a fugitive charged with second degree murder and escape.&#10;&#10;It is also worth noting that the red-bearded man may have some connection to Jake, the girl who escaped with Ben from the Inn in Hoover City on Venus. The story mentions that Ben sees a tri-dimensional photo of a rock-faced man in a merchant spaceman's uniform with a neatly trimmed red beard in his room on Venus, and that this image haunts him in his sleep. It is possible that the red-bearded man is Jake's father or another member of her group of spacemen who operate beyond Mars and have established a base on an asteroid." />
