    <node id="1. The people living on the asteroid are a group of renegade spacemen who operate beyond Mars. They consist of about a thousand individuals and have a dozen ships. Half of them are wanted by the Interplanetary Bureau of Investigation (I.B.I.), while the others are physical or psycho rejects who cannot return to Earth even if they wanted to.&#10;2. These spacemen have established a base on an asteroid where they can operate freely and make an honest living by transporting cargo and supplies to frontier ports like Hoover City. They are described as misfits and rejectees from the clearing houses on Earth, and they have formed their own community beyond the reach of Earth's laws and society.&#10;3. The renegade spacemen are able to interact with frontier ports like Hoover City without raising objections from authorities because the I.B.I. has too many problems to search for them in the frontiers. Additionally, the frontier ports rely on these spacemen for transportation of cargo and supplies. The renegade spacemen are accepted as a necessary part of life in the frontier ports, despite their outlaw status." />
    <node id="Ben's sudden anger outburst toward Cobb in the bar was likely due to a combination of factors. First, Cobb had been persistently following and taunting him, which may have worn down Ben's patience. Additionally, Cobb had questioned Ben's decision to join the space exploration mission and called him a sucker, which may have struck a nerve as Ben had worked hard to achieve his dream of becoming a junior astrogation officer. The fact that Cobb was drunk and seemingly unaware of the significance of Ben's uniform may have also contributed to Ben's frustration. These factors, combined with Ben's own stress and fear from being a fugitive charged with second degree murder and escape, likely led to his explosive reaction and physical attack on Cobb." />
    <node id=" of whiskey.&#10; &#10; Ben stiffened. He was twenty-four and dressed in the white, crimson-braided uniform of the Odyssey's junior astrogation officer. He was three months out of the Academy at White Sands and the shining uniform was like a key to all the mysteries of the Universe.&#10; &#10; He'd sought long for that key.&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; At the age of five—perhaps in order to dull the memory of his parents' death in a recent strato-jet crash—he'd spent hours watching the night sky for streaking flame-tails of Moon rockets. At ten, he'd ground his first telescope. At fourteen, he'd converted an abandoned shed on the government boarding-school grounds to a retreat which housed his collection of astronomy and rocketry books.&#10; &#10; At sixteen, he'd spent every weekend holiday hitchhiking from Boys Town No. 5 in the Catskills to Long Island Spaceport. There, among the grizzled veterans of the old Moon Patrol, he'd found friends who understood his dream and who later recommended his appointment to the U. S. Academy for the Conquest of Space.&#10; &#10; And a month ago, he'd signed aboard the Odyssey —the first ship" />
    <node id="The red-bearded man is a powerful figure who is significant to Ben's restless sleep because Ben believes that this giant can help him deal with his past as a junior astrogation officer and his current status as a fugitive charged with second degree murder and escape. The dead man, named Cobb, has become an invisible Siamese twin to Ben, haunting his thoughts and dreams. Ben wants to forget a living man like Cobb, but his death has made him an inseparable part of Ben's life. The red-bearded man may be a member of Jake's group of spacemen who operate beyond Mars and have established a base on an asteroid. Ben hopes to find the red-bearded man because he believes that this giant can help him escape from Cobb and his haunting presence. Additionally, Maggie, a woman who helps Ben, reveals that the red-bearded man is her husband and an astrogator who needs a good man like Ben for their group." />
    <node id="Ben Curtis is a spaceman who is pursuing a red-bearded giant, though it is unclear why. He has recently arrived on Venus, specifically in Hoover City, after realizing that the memory of the dead man's face he saw during his last space flight is haunting him and he hopes to escape it by exploring alien worlds. Ben enters the Blast Inn, a seedy bar with a variety of patrons and a dimly lit atmosphere, while being followed by a dead man. He is looking for the red-bearded giant, but is also hiding from the police, as his description has likely been circulated along with a reward for his capture. The situation in the bar becomes tense when policemen charge towards him with neuro-clubs raised and one of them yells at him to stop. Ben tries to make a run for it, but a projectile is fired near him, making the situation even more dangerous and confusing." />
    <node id="Yes, even though the man had been wounded and was on the verge of complete lethargy, he still insisted on trying to escape with the help of a woman. She had warned him that he might die if he didn't give himself up, but he refused to change his mind. This is evident when the man tried to stumble toward the exit after hearing heavy footsteps and realizing that someone was approaching them. The woman then guided him, helping him escape by pushing and pulling him in a different direction before closing a door behind them." />
    <node id="1. The text states that after Ben struck Cobb and realized he was dead, &quot;for a single absurd second, Ben was seized with terror.&quot; This terror is not explicitly explained, but it seems to be related to the reality of having just killed a man and the immediate aftermath of the act. Ben's fear may have been triggered by the shock of what he had done, the potential consequences of his actions, or the sudden silence and emptiness of the barroom once he realized that everyone else had fled the scene.&#10;2. Additionally, Ben's behavior following the fight, including his hasty escape and hiding in a dark corner while smoking a cigarette, suggests that he was experiencing fear, guilt, and disorientation after realizing what he had done. He may have been afraid of being caught and punished for his actions, or he may have felt guilty about taking another person's life, even if it was in self-defense.&#10;3. The text also notes that Ben was a fugitive charged with second degree murder and escape at the time of the fight, which suggests that he was already on the run from the law and had likely experienced fear and stress related to his legal situation. Therefore, it is possible that these existing fears and anxieties contributed to his terror after striking Cobb and prompted him to flee the scene.&#10;&#10;In summary, Ben's terror after hitting Cobb seems to be a complex emotional response triggered by a combination of factors, including shock, guilt, fear of punishment, and anxiety related to his existing legal situation as a fugitive." />
    <node id="1. The asteroid miners plan to move their operations further into the frontier if there is a crackdown or when Space Corps ships officially reach the asteroids. They have already established a new base on an asteroid, beyond the reach of Earth's laws and society.&#10;2. The asteroid miners are able to continue their operations despite objections from authorities because they provide necessary transportation of cargo and supplies to frontier ports like Hoover City. They also have friends planted in the Interplanetary Bureau of Investigation (I.B.I.), making it difficult for the authorities to ignore them.&#10;3. The asteroid miners consist of about a thousand individuals with a dozen ships, half of whom are wanted by the I.B.I., while the others are physical or psycho rejects who cannot return to Earth even if they wanted to. They have formed their own community and have established a base on an asteroid where they can operate freely.&#10;4. The red-bearded man that Ben meets could potentially be a member of the asteroid miners' group, who may help Ben deal with his past as a junior astrogation officer and his current status as a fugitive charged with second degree murder and escape." />
    <node id="&#10; &quot;Don't the authorities object?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Not very strongly. The I. B. I. has too many problems right here to search the whole System for a few two-bit crooks. Besides, we carry cargoes of almost pure uranium and tungsten and all the stuff that's scarce on Earth and Mars and Venus. Nobody really cares whether it comes from the asteroids or Hades. If we want to risk our lives mining it, that's our business.&quot;&#10; &#10; She pursed her lips. &quot;But if they guessed how strong we are or that we have friends planted in the I. B. I.—well, things might be different. There probably would be a crackdown.&quot;&#10; &#10; Ben scowled. &quot;What happens if there is a crackdown? And what will you do when Space Corps ships officially reach the asteroids? They can't ignore you then.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Then we move on. We dream up new gimmicks for our crates and take them to Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune, Pluto. In time, maybe, we'll be pushed out of the System itself. Maybe it won't be the white-suited boys who'll make that first hop to the stars. It could be us" />
    <node id="The lights in the room are turned on by someone or something unspecified in the story. However, Ben Curtis suspects that it might be the Martian kid because of the boy's apparent ability to read his mind and know what he is thinking. Earlier in the story, when Ben wanted to sit in the shadows, the Martian boy had said, &quot;A tres fine table. Close in the shadows&quot; even though Ben had not explicitly expressed this desire. This made Ben wonder how the boy knew what he was thinking, leading him to suspect that the Martian kid might be responsible for turning on the lights in an attempt to reveal him to the police. However, there is no explicit confirmation in the story that the Martian boy is responsible for turning on the lights." />
    <node id="1. The man's determination to walk again stems from his past achievement as a Space Corps officer, which represents his and Jake's shared dream of staying in space and working with rockets. He sees walking again as the key to rejoining the Space Corps and continuing his work with rockets, which is a source of hope for him. His guilt over his past actions and the constant haunting memory of the person he can't forget also fuel his desire to walk again and leave his failures behind.&#10;2. The man's Space Corps background has instilled in him the values of honesty, loyalty, and duty, which he sees as essential for humanity to break free from the limitations of Earth and explore the stars. He remembers a little picture book his mother gave him with captions like &quot;A Space Officer Is Honest&quot; and &quot;A Space Officer Is Loyal,&quot; which symbolize the principles that have allowed mankind to achieve great feats in space exploration. These trite words hold significant meaning for him, as they represent the values that he once stood for and wants to uphold again." />
    <node id="1. The renegade spacemen operating from the Solar System's frontiers are a group of misfits and rejectees from the clearing houses on Earth. They consist of about a thousand individuals with a dozen ships, half of whom are wanted by the Interplanetary Bureau of Investigation (I.B.I.), while the others are physical or psycho rejects who cannot return to Earth even if they wanted to.&#10;2. Their purpose is to operate freely and make an honest living by transporting cargo and supplies to frontier ports like Hoover City, beyond the reach of Earth's laws and society. They have established a base on an asteroid and are accepted as a necessary part of life in the frontier ports despite their outlaw status.&#10;3. The renegade spacemen are not outlaws in the traditional sense, but rather individuals who cannot return to Earth and have formed their own community in the frontiers. They provide necessary transportation of cargo and supplies to the frontier ports, making it difficult for authorities to ignore them despite objections from some officials." />
